  "text": "To compensate for the neutralizing effect of salivary bicarbonate, hypopharyngeal data were reanalyzed using pH 5 as the reflux threshold. This is in line with the findings of Jack et al [CITATION_1] who detected gastric acid in the trachea with pH up to 5. However, increasing the threshold pH at the hypopharyngeal electrode from 4 to 5 still did not differentiate children with GER and respiratory symptoms (group D) from those with GER alone (group C). Indeed, children in group C (ie, those without respiratory symptoms) refluxed to the hypopharynx on average of 3.4 times per hour. This supports the conclusions reached by Hampton et al [CITATION_2] that host mechanisms such as the competence of the laryngeal inlet may be more important determinants of aspiration rather than the bquantityQ of gastric acid refluxed to the hypopharynx. In the presence of a competent laryngeal inlet, repeated reflux episodes to the hypopharynx will not result in aspiration.",
